quick_rationale: Amine-decorated Al MOF gives high CO2 affinity and selectivity; Al nodes are relatively water tolerant; regeneration is moderate temperature; synthesis is scalable but pelletization is still needed.

Open Mg sites give strong low-pressure CO2 binding; water strongly coadsorbs and can slow or degrade performance; regeneration is moderate but water adds energy; scale-up is possible yet shaping must manage pressure drop.
Hydrophobic and chemically robust; intrinsic CO2 affinity in the Henry region is low so 400 ppm working capacity is limited; regeneration is easy; industrial shaping is feasible.
Very high surface area but weak low-pressure CO2 affinity; hydrolyzes with water so humid-air operation is poor; regeneration is easy; shaping is difficult due to fragility.

Li+ exchange can raise CO2 affinity and selectivity versus the parent; humidity tolerance and long cycling under wet air are not well proven; regeneration should be moderate; indium content and synthesis complexity hurt scale.

Porous indium framework can adsorb CO2 but low-ppm performance is not a primary design target; humidity behavior is uncertain; regeneration is likely easy; indium cost and synthesis reduce practical scale.
Large-pore MOF favors high-pressure capacity over Henry-region uptake; humid-air behavior is not well established; regeneration is easy; scale and shaping remain less mature than robust adsorbents.

Good CO2 uptake from open Cu sites but water competes and can hydrolyze the framework; regeneration is moderate and cycling depends on moisture management; extrusion and pelletization are possible but long-term humid stability is a key risk.

High porosity is advantageous but low-pressure CO2 affinity is typically modest in large pores; humidity impact is uncertain; regeneration is easy; practical shaping and long cycling data for DAC are limited.

Developed and evaluated as formulated particles for pressure swing operation; CO2 affinity at 400 ppm is not the focus; humidity tolerance is unclear; regeneration via PSA is practical but DAC maturity is low.

Open Mg sites give strong low-pressure CO2 binding; water strongly coadsorbs and can slow or degrade performance; regeneration is moderate but water adds energy; scale-up is possible yet shaping must manage pressure drop.

Open Ni sites provide high CO2 affinity and selectivity; water coadsorption is strong and can reduce working capacity; regeneration is moderate temperature; scalable synthesis exists but complete activation is critical.

High cation charge density in rho-ZMOF can increase Henry-region CO2 affinity; ionic frameworks can be water robust but water loading can be high; regeneration can be modest if water is managed; scale-up and shaping are less mature.

Open Mg sites give strong low-pressure CO2 binding; water strongly coadsorbs and can slow or degrade performance; regeneration is moderate but water adds energy; scale-up is possible yet shaping must manage pressure drop.

Open Mn sites give decent low-pressure CO2 uptake; humidity sensitivity and competitive water adsorption remain major; regeneration is moderate; synthesis and shaping are less industrialized than zeolites.

Cation-exchanged rho-ZMOF can show higher CO2 affinity than monovalent forms; water uptake is also expected to be strong; regeneration needs moisture control; ion exchange adds processing steps and shaping maturity is limited.

Open Co sites can bind CO2 strongly at low pressure; water competes for sites and can impact stability; regeneration is moderate; scale-up exists in lab and pilot contexts but shaping adds complexity.

High cation charge density in rho-ZMOF can increase Henry-region CO2 affinity; ionic frameworks can be water robust but water loading can be high; regeneration can be modest if water is managed; scale-up and shaping are less mature.

Open Mg sites give strong low-pressure CO2 binding; water strongly coadsorbs and can slow or degrade performance; regeneration is moderate but water adds energy; scale-up is possible yet shaping must manage pressure drop.

Open Fe sites can bind CO2 strongly but may be more reactive toward water; humidity stability and cycling are concerns; regeneration is moderate; practical shaping and activation control are required for scale.
Divalent Mg2+ exchange can boost CO2 Henry constant in rho-ZMOF; water uptake likely increases as well; regeneration requires moisture management; ion exchange and shaping add complexity.

Extra hydroxide ligation is predicted to resist water coordination; experimental DAC-relevant CO2 data and scale-up are limited; regeneration should be easy; scandium cost makes large-scale deployment unlikely.
Lower CO2 binding strength than Mg or Ni analogs; still moisture sensitive due to open sites; regeneration is easier; industrial maturity is modest and pelletization is required.
High charge density Li+ can increase Henry-region CO2 affinity; water uptake can also rise and may dominate in humid air; regeneration needs moisture control; ion exchange adds processing complexity.

Core-shell zeolite@MOF combines robust shaped zeolite cores with high-affinity MOF shell; still water competitive but form factor is stronger than pure MOF powders; regeneration can use TSA or VSA; scalable forming is plausible.

Cooperative chemisorption yields very high CO2 affinity at trace concentrations; literature reports strong performance with water present; regeneration can be relatively low barrier; synthesis and shaping at scale remain developing.
Cation-exchanged rho-ZMOF shows increased CO2 uptake and can be regenerated after removing cage water near 100 C; water loading can still dominate; scale-up needs robust pelletization protocols.

Residual solvent and solvent-derived defects can block open metal sites and cut low-pressure working capacity; water still competes strongly; regeneration is easier but performance drops; highlights activation sensitivity for scale.

Divalent Sr2+ exchange can increase CO2 affinity in rho-ZMOF relative to monovalent forms; water uptake is also expected to be strong; regeneration needs moisture control; scale-up maturity is limited.

Cooperative chemisorption yields very high CO2 affinity at trace concentrations; reported to maintain strong capture in the presence of water; regeneration can be relatively low barrier; scale-up and shaping are the main unknowns.

Well-established platform for amine-appended cooperative DAC with high 400 ppm uptake and good cycling; moisture tolerance depends on functionalization and process; regeneration is typically moderate temperature; monolith supports improve pressure drop and scale.

Open Ni sites provide high CO2 affinity and selectivity; water coadsorption is strong and can reduce working capacity; regeneration is moderate temperature; scalable synthesis exists but complete activation is critical.
Cation-exchanged rho-ZMOF shows increased CO2 uptake and can be regenerated after removing cage water near 100 C; water loading can still dominate; scale-up needs robust pelletization protocols.

Preloading water illustrates strong competition at open metal sites and reduced CO2 capacity; regeneration energy increases due to desorbing water; practical humid-air operation would require drying or hydrophobic strategies to preserve working capacity.

Framework is relatively robust to moisture compared with many carboxylate MOFs; CO2 affinity at 400 ppm is moderate; regeneration should be easy; scalable synthesis is plausible but DAC-specific cycling and shaping data are limited.

Microporous Cu MOF with high CO2 uptake and selectivity at ambient conditions; humidity tolerance is not fully established and copper nodes can be moisture sensitive; regeneration is moderate; synthesis complexity and shaping data are limited.

Ultramicroporous fluorinated pillars give exceptional low-pressure CO2 uptake; humidity can quickly saturate sites and suppress CO2 unless managed; regeneration via mild TSA is feasible; scale-up depends on stability under cycling.

Zr-based UiO offers high moisture stability and the hybrid improves shaping and transport; intrinsic low-pressure CO2 affinity is moderate without strong chemisorption sites; regeneration is easy; practical form factor supports scale-up.

Aminated GO composites can increase CO2 uptake and may improve moisture resistance versus pristine Cu-BTC; still limited by copper-node water chemistry; regeneration is moderate; composite processing aids shaping.

Rho-topology ZMOFs show decent CO2 uptake and can be tuned via ion exchange; humid air can fill cages with water and reduce CO2 capacity; regeneration can be modest if water is removed; scale-up remains early.

K+ exchange can tune CO2 uptake and selectivity in rho-ZMOF; water uptake can still dominate in humid conditions; regeneration needs moisture control; ion exchange and shaping maturity limit deployment.

Very strong low-pressure CO2 adsorption and commercially scalable pellets; water strongly competes and raises regeneration energy in humid air; regenerable by TSA or VSA; best with upstream drying or structured contactors.

Copper-carboxylate MOFs can have good CO2 uptake but are often moisture sensitive; some show reversible water-driven structural changes; regeneration can be moderate; practical scale depends heavily on humid stability and shaping.

Residual solvent and defects can block open metal sites and reduce low-pressure CO2 working capacity; water still competes strongly; regeneration is easier but usable capacity drops; activation control is a key scale-up issue.
Predicted to resist water coordination due to hydroxide balance but experimental adsorption data are scarce; scandium cost is prohibitive; regeneration should be easy; scale-up is unlikely.

High CO2 affinity and established pellet scale; slightly higher Si Al can reduce hydrophilicity but water still competes strongly; regenerable by TSA or VSA; humid-air DAC usually needs drying or staged contactors.

UiO-66 family is among the most moisture stable MOFs; hydroxyl functionality can raise CO2 affinity and enable water-influenced uptake; regeneration is easy; pellets and composites are well studied for scale.

Strong low-pressure CO2 adsorption and mature industrial forming; water competes strongly and increases regeneration energy; regenerable by TSA or VSA; best performance in DAC requires moisture management.

Graphene oxide supported MOF composites can improve kinetics and handling versus neat powders; CO2 capacity gains depend on composite quality; humidity tolerance is still limited by MOF chemistry; regeneration is moderate and shaping is feasible.
Water-stable Al framework, but amine increases water uptake and can suppress CO2 at realistic humidity; scalable pelletization is plausible.
Cation-exchanged ionic framework can strengthen low-pressure CO2 affinity, but humidity competition and scale/shaping remain less demonstrated than zeolites.
Industrial zeolite form factor and fast kinetics; core–shell can aid shaping and diffusion control, but strong water co-adsorption limits humid-air performance.
Open Ni sites give strong low-pressure CO2 binding, yet water readily competes for those sites; shaping is feasible but long humid cycling is a risk.
High-porosity ionic framework can show CO2 selectivity, but evidence for low-ppm capture and humid durability is limited and shaping/scale is uncertain.
Commercially relevant zeolite family with strong CO2 uptake at low pressure; core–shell structures help processing, but humid air still penalizes capacity.
Moderate CO2 uptake typical of physisorbing Zn MOFs; humidity tolerance and structured contactor readiness are not well established for DAC duty.
Strong low-pressure CO2 adsorption from open Mg sites, but water strongly competes and can degrade performance in humid air; regeneration is easy if kept dry.
Cu–carboxylate framework reported for selective gas adsorption, but Cu nodes are typically moisture sensitive and low-ppm performance/shaping data are sparse.
Mesoporous silica has weak intrinsic CO2 affinity at ppm; it becomes relevant mainly as a support for grafted/impregnated amines rather than as-is.
Cu coordination framework with limited public data for humid, low-ppm CO2 capture; likely needs functionalization or composite shaping to be competitive.
Triazolate framework family can provide strong CO2 interactions; however, humid-air performance is typically better in hydroxide-modified analogs than in chloride forms.
Excellent low-pressure CO2 binding via open metal sites, but humid air rapidly fills or displaces those sites; regeneration is mild but requires moisture control.
Hydroxyl-lined, water-stable Al MOF shows strong CO2 selectivity and better moisture tolerance than open-metal-site MOFs; still limited demonstration at atmospheric ppm.
Graphene-oxide/MOF hybrids can improve mass transfer and handling versus powder MOFs; humidity robustness depends on the MOF and salt/IL additive and is not universal.
Amino-functionalized Cu-BTC can increase CO2 affinity, but Cu paddlewheel frameworks remain moisture-sensitive and may lose capacity/structure under humid cycling.
Cheap and hydrophobic with easy regeneration and scalable shaping, but weak CO2 affinity at ~400 ppm generally limits working capacity without added amines/alkali sites.
Cation-exchanged anionic In framework can enhance CO2 affinity at low pressure; moisture tolerance may be reasonable, but industrial shaping and cycling data are limited.
Very high cation density gives strong CO2 uptake/selectivity at low pressure and excellent scalability, but water co-adsorption is severe in ambient humidity.
GO/MOF composites can improve handling and sometimes CO2 uptake, yet performance in humid air and long-cycle stability depend strongly on the specific formulation.
Same MOF-74(Mg) chemistry: strong CO2 at low pressure but water competes strongly; morphology changes may help kinetics but not the fundamental humidity penalty.
X-type zeolite with divalent cations offers strong CO2 adsorption and established pellet forms; humid air reduces capacity via competitive water uptake.
LTA-type zeolite in an industrially mature form; decent CO2 affinity but strong hydrophilicity makes humid-air DAC challenging without pretreatment or process tricks.
Preloaded water occupies high-energy sites in MOF-74, sharply reducing low-ppm CO2 working capacity; may help stability but typically hurts DAC performance.
Amine-appended cooperative adsorption can deliver high selectivity and usable capacity at very low CO2 partial pressures; regeneration is practical but humidity management remains important.
Open Mg sites provide strong CO2 binding and fast kinetics, but humid air deactivates sites; shaped forms are possible but need robust water management.
Cation-exchanged X zeolite combines high scalability with strong CO2 adsorption at low pressure; performance drops in humidity due to water competition.
Activated carbon variant with good microporosity and easy cycling, but typically insufficient CO2 affinity at atmospheric ppm unless chemically functionalized.
Faujasite family is manufacturable at scale and has strong CO2 adsorption, yet water co-adsorption in ambient air is the key limiter for DAC duty.
PEI-impregnated MIL-101 is demonstrated for ~400 ppm capture and can tolerate humidity better than many physisorbents; regeneration energy and amine stability are the trade-offs.
Hydroxide-containing Cu frameworks can show strong CO2 interactions, but DAC readiness hinges on humid cycling stability and scalable shaping, which are less documented.
Ni-MOF-74 offers strong CO2 binding at low pressure, but water displaces CO2 at open metal sites; powder-to-structured shaping is feasible yet adds complexity.
Workhorse industrial adsorbent with strong CO2 affinity and robust pellets; main drawback is high water uptake that suppresses capacity under humid air.
Zr-based MOF has high stability but is optimized for larger-gas storage rather than strong low-pressure CO2 binding; DAC performance likely limited without functionalization.
Cation tuning in rho-type ionic frameworks can increase CO2 affinity and selectivity; humidity effects and large-scale structuring remain less proven than zeolites.
Small-pore SAPO-RHO zeolite can show strong CO2 selectivity at low pressure with good processability; humidity still competes but SAPO frameworks can be less hydrophilic than NaX.
High-surface-area MOF is more suited to high-pressure storage than ppm capture; water stability and pelletization are variable across PCN families.
IRMOF/MOF-5 family materials are typically hydrolytically fragile, making humid-air cycling difficult despite high surface area; shaping/scale is also challenging.
Sodium-impregnated N-doped porous carbon can boost CO2 affinity vs plain carbons while retaining low-cost shaping; long humid cycling and oxidative stability are the open questions.
GO/MOF hybrids can improve handling and sometimes stability, but Cu-based MOF components remain moisture-sensitive; DAC value depends on demonstrated humid cycling.
Activated carbon sample with good microporosity and scalable shaping, but limited low-ppm capacity without strong chemisorption functionality.
Very scalable LTA zeolite but generally weaker CO2 affinity than X/LSX and strongly hydrophilic; humid-air DAC performance is typically constrained.
Urea/GO-modified Cu-BTC can increase CO2 uptake and may improve handling, but Cu paddlewheel hydrolysis risk persists under humidity and cycling.
Repeated cycling indicates some regenerability, but gradual structural/active-site loss is plausible for Cu-BTC derivatives in realistic humid operation.
CNT/MOF composites can aid heat and mass transfer and improve shaping, yet Cu-BTC moisture sensitivity remains the main limitation for humid-air DAC.
Graphite oxide composites can modestly enhance CO2 uptake/kinetics and handling versus pure Cu-BTC, but long-term humid stability of Cu nodes remains a concern.
Process-optimized Cu-BTC can raise CO2/N2 separation metrics, but intrinsic humidity sensitivity and limited low-ppm validation constrain DAC potential.
Zn-MOF-74 provides open metal sites but generally weaker CO2 binding than Mg/Ni analogs and still suffers strong water competition; practical shaping is moderate.
High-surface-area IRMOF is usually moisture sensitive and relies on weak physisorption at low pressure; humid-air DAC cycling and shaping are challenging.
Large-pore MOF can store gases at higher pressure but typically lacks strong CO2 affinity at ppm; moisture tolerance and scale-up depend on synthesis and stability.
Bio-derived/anionic MOFs can offer polar binding sites for CO2, but DAC-relevant humid cycling, regeneration energy, and structured forms are not broadly proven.
Ionic-liquid impregnation can enhance CO2 affinity and sometimes mitigate water effects, but it can also block pores and complicate regeneration and stability.
MIL-53(Al) is relatively scalable and stable; conductive carbon additives can help shaping/heat transfer, but humid-air CO2 working capacity is still limited by water uptake.
Cycling data suggest reversible adsorption, but Cu-BTC derivatives generally face moisture-driven degradation that can reduce long-term DAC performance.
Open-metal-site MOF-74 chemistry provides strong CO2 binding, but copper variants are especially prone to water-induced deactivation and framework instability.
SAPO-RHO (DNL-6) zeolite shows strong CO2 selectivity at low pressure and is structurally robust; humid air remains the main penalty, though potentially less severe than NaX.
Later-cycle performance points to cumulative losses typical of moisture/defect sensitivity in Cu-BTC composites; workable if protected from water and contaminants.
Nanosizing improves kinetics for PEI/MIL-101 DAC sorbents; demonstrated low-ppm capture with humidity tolerance, with trade-offs in amine stability and regeneration energy.
Rare-earth MOF composition suggests good hydrolytic robustness, but DAC-relevant CO2 isotherms, humid cycling, and scalable shaping are not clearly established.
More activated/microporous carbon can modestly improve low-pressure CO2 uptake while keeping low-cost shaping and easy regeneration; still typically below chemisorbent performance at ppm.
Ultramicroporous ion-exchanged framework gives strong low-pressure CO2 affinity; humidity can compete for sites and large-scale shaping evidence is limited.
Triazolate MOF family is chemically robust, but CO2 capture at DAC-relevant partial pressures and humid-air cycling performance are not well established.
Easily shaped, industrially compatible zeolite with good low-pressure CO2 selectivity; water co-adsorption can strongly reduce working capacity in humid air.
Alkali-impregnated N-doped carbon boosts CO2 affinity while remaining humidity-tolerant and scalable; performance depends strongly on alkali loading and regeneration strategy.
Hydrophobic ZIFs can preserve CO2 selectivity under humidity, but ppm-level working capacity is typically limited and scale-up/shaping evidence for DAC is sparse.
Open-metal sites give strong low-pressure CO2 binding, but water strongly competes at these sites, making humid-air cycling challenging without mitigation.
RF-derived carbon aerogels are humidity-tolerant and can be monolith-shaped; DAC performance is usually constrained by physisorptive CO2 binding unless pore chemistry is tuned.
UTSA-16 offers strong ultramicropore-driven low-pressure CO2 selectivity and can be processed with polymer binder; humidity and long-cycle pellet durability still need careful control.
Diamine functionalization enables chemisorption suited to very low CO2 partial pressures; key risks are humid O2 stability, heat management, and scalable shaping validation.
Low-cost, scalable, humidity-tolerant carbon; ppm-level capture is limited by weak physisorption unless ultramicropores or basic sites are engineered.
FAU zeolite is readily pelletized and process-ready; strong water uptake in humid air can suppress CO2 working capacity unless formulation/silica level is optimized.
Similar scalability and humidity tolerance as other carbons, but typical working capacity at 400 ppm is modest without strong ultramicropore/chemistry optimization.
N-rich aerogel surfaces can increase CO2 affinity and remain moisture-tolerant; still generally physisorption-limited at ppm and aerogel processing can be nontrivial at scale.
Polydopamine-derived N-doped carbon coatings can add basic sites and robustness; DAC performance hinges on achieving ultramicroporosity and stable surface chemistry through cycling.
Higher activation often increases ultramicroporosity and low-pressure uptake, but capture remains physisorptive and may require deeper vacuum or larger contactors for DAC.
Water-stable Al-MOF shows humidity-resilient CO2 affinity and demonstrated shaping/monolith routes; ppm-level working capacity is moderate but regeneration is favorable.
Hydrothermally robust framework with practical regeneration, but largely physisorptive CO2 binding gives modest ppm working capacity unless amine-functionalized.
KOH-activated N-doped carbon can deliver strong ultramicroporosity and improved CO2 affinity; humidity tolerance and scalability are good, but regeneration may be vacuum-intensive.
Exceptional moisture stability and form-factor options; unfunctionalized CO2 capture at 400 ppm is moderate and may need functionalization or optimized cycling to excel.
Acid-treated N-doped carbon can alter basic sites and porosity; scalable and humidity-tolerant, but ppm capture is typically limited without strong ultramicropore control.
Same open-metal-site benefits as CPO-27-Mg but higher nonporous fraction/binder typically dilutes capacity; humid air still strongly competes at adsorption sites.
Cooperative amine chemisorption gives steep uptake at DAC partial pressures; moderate humidity can enhance capture and monolith-supported forms improve practical deployment.
Cooperative chemisorption persists with partial hydration; moderate water can assist uptake, but excess co-adsorbed water can slow kinetics and raise regeneration energy.
Humidity-resilient Al-MOF with demonstrated stability and shaping pathways; ppm working capacity is moderate but regeneration/cycling robustness are favorable.
Strong low-pressure CO2 selectivity in powder form, but practical implementation depends on shaping strategy and managing humidity and pressure drop.
Zeolite A is readily shaped and can adsorb CO2 strongly at low pressure; high water affinity often dominates under humid air and reduces CO2 working capacity.
Ultramicroporous zeolite with strong framework stability and CO2 selectivity; humid-air capture is commonly limited by water co-adsorption.
Reported as a high-uptake CO2 adsorbent with strong binding motifs; key uncertainties are long-term hydrothermal stability and scalable shaping evidence.
Strong low-pressure CO2 adsorption and fast kinetics from open sites; humidity competition can cause large capacity losses and complicate cyclic operation.
Composite can improve thermal conductivity for cyclic adsorption while retaining MIL-53 stability; DAC performance remains moderate and composite processing must preserve porosity.
IRMOF family is moisture-sensitive with rapid porosity loss, making humid-air capture and repeated regeneration impractical without protective modifications.
Binder-enabled shaping improves practicality with limited regeneration penalty; overall performance trades off capacity against mechanical durability and humidity management.
Water-stable MIL-96 variants can sustain CO2 affinity under moderate humidity and are shapeable; DAC working capacity is moderate but cycling/regeneration are favorable.
Open-metal-site triazolate framework supports relatively strong CO2 adsorption; humidity can still compete and deployment depends on robust shaping into low-pressure-drop forms.
Commercially scalable and easily shaped, but weak ppm-level binding limits DAC efficiency without chemical functionalization or very large contactors/vacuum swings.
Rare-earth fcu-MOF platform can tune CO2 adsorption energetics via polar interiors; promising low-pressure affinity but rare-earth cost and scale/shaping remain hurdles.
Higher binder fraction typically improves robustness but dilutes capacity; still benefits from UTSA-16 ultramicropore selectivity if humidity is managed.
Amino-acid-functional multivariate design can increase CO2 affinity and potentially tolerate humidity; limited industrial shaping and long-cycle validation data so far.
Ionic porous polymer network boosts CO2 affinity and can be processed into robust forms; ppm-level working capacity and humidity response need application-specific validation.
Charged ultramicroporous framework can yield strong CO2 selectivity at low pressure; practical shaping, humid-air cycling, and scale-up data appear limited.
High-porosity COF is mostly physisorptive with typically weak binding at ppm; competitive DAC use generally requires functionalization and stable shaping.
PEI impregnation enables strong chemisorption and humidity-enhanced uptake; challenges are oxidative aging, diffusion limits with high-MW PEI, and heat management in shaped forms.
Very high amine density can raise DAC capacity, but mass-transfer limitations and regeneration energy typically increase and long-term stability must be controlled.
Added conductive filler can help thermal management but dilutes sorbent mass; CO2 uptake remains moderate and humidity effects must be balanced against cycling needs.
Robust, regenerable framework but mostly physisorptive CO2 binding; typically needs amine functionalization to achieve strong DAC working capacity.
Ultramicroporous selectivity supports low-pressure capture with relatively mild regeneration; deployment hinges on shaping choice and managing water co-adsorption.
Bare mesoporous silica has weak CO2 binding at ppm; effective DAC generally requires amine loading on the support to create chemisorption sites.
Humidity-tolerant Al-MOF family with demonstrated stability and monolith processing; ppm working capacity is moderate but regeneration/cycling are favorable.
Heavy water occupation blocks open metal sites, sharply reducing CO2 uptake and increasing regeneration burden; repeated humid cycling can drive large capacity loss.
Bio-MOF pore decoration improves water stability and can enhance CO2/N2 selectivity; absolute ppm working capacity and industrial shaping evidence are still limited.
Water-stable Zr-MOF with GO improving heat transfer/shaping; CO2 affinity mostly physisorption so DAC capacity is moderate.
Sulfonated porous polymer adds strong polar sites and is chemically robust, but water can compete and uptake at 400 ppm is limited.
MOF/GO composite retains UTSA-16 selectivity and can better manage humidity; still needs careful cycling control for real air streams.
Ionic sulfonate sites boost low-pressure CO2 affinity and maintain polymer stability; humidity can reduce working capacity but regeneration is feasible.
CHA-type zeolite offers strong CO2/N2 selectivity and scalable shaping, yet water co-adsorption can suppress CO2 capture in humid air.
High-surface-area MOF with decent CO2 uptake, but limited ultra-dilute affinity and uncertain humid-air performance without functionalization.
Amine-functional MOF improves CO2 affinity versus parent framework, but humidity tolerance and scalable shaping remain mid-tier.
Ultramicroporous biomass-derived carbon can adsorb CO2 at low pressures and regenerates easily, but selectivity at 400 ppm is modest.
Open-metal-site MOF-74 chemistry gives strong CO2 binding, but dilution/shaping plus water sensitivity lowers humid-air DAC practicality.
Breathing Al-MOF is relatively water-stable and regenerable, yet low-ppm uptake is moderate and performance is sensitive to humidity/structure state.
Likely carbon-type adsorbent with good stability and easy regeneration, but physisorption limits ultra-dilute CO2 working capacity.
Water-stable Al-MOF with polar pores supports moderate low-pressure CO2 capture and practical shaping, though not strong chemisorption.
Composite carbon form improves handling/shaping and cycling, but CO2 capture remains physisorption-limited at ambient ppm levels.
Cu–btc framework can bind CO2, but Cu nodes are moisture-sensitive and shaping/cycling stability are concerns for humid DAC.
Porous MOF likely offers moderate CO2 uptake, yet humid-air stability and practical shaping data are limited.
Activated carbon is scalable and humidity-tolerant with easy regeneration, but low-ppm CO2 capacity is typically moderate.
GO/IL–MOF composite can increase CO2 affinity and improve heat management, but performance depends on pore blocking and ionic-liquid stability.
Likely carbon-based adsorbent; robust and regenerable but limited intrinsic affinity for 400 ppm CO2 without functional groups.
More GO can aid shaping/thermal conductivity but may block microporosity; overall CO2 affinity remains moderate under DAC conditions.
Binder-shaped UTSA-16 improves mechanical handling and cycling, with modest capacity penalty; humid-air kinetics still matter.
Hydrophobic ZIF helps against humidity, but weak CO2 binding at ultra-dilute partial pressures limits DAC working capacity.
Rare-earth MOF likely offers good framework stability but limited low-ppm CO2 affinity and high material cost for scale-up.
Alkyl-amine functionalization modestly boosts CO2 affinity; humidity sensitivity and scaling/shaping keep it mid-range.
Trapdoor-like zeolite behavior can deliver very high CO2 selectivity, but water and kinetic constraints can complicate real-air operation.
High-porosity MOF can store CO2, yet humid stability and low-ppm working capacity are uncertain without stronger binding sites.
GO can improve composite handling and heat transfer, but Cu-BTC moisture sensitivity and cycling loss reduce DAC robustness.
Zn4O-carboxylate family frameworks tend to hydrolyze in humidity, making long-term humid-air DAC operation unlikely.
Resorcinol–formaldehyde-derived carbon is stable and easily regenerated, but physisorption limits capture at ambient ppm levels.
Higher GO loading can aid heat management and shaping, but risks pore blocking; overall UTSA-16 selectivity remains the main advantage.
Pd-based porous coordination material is likely stable but expensive, and CO2 uptake/selectivity at 400 ppm is typically limited.
Early-cycle composite shows reasonable CO2 uptake, but humidity-driven degradation and gradual capacity loss are expected.
Initial performance can be good due to added interfaces, but moisture sensitivity of the Cu-BTC component remains a key risk.
Low GO fraction may slightly improve shaping while retaining pores; humid stability is still constrained by Cu-BTC chemistry.
Al-MOF with good hydrothermal stability and moderate CO2 affinity; regenerable and shapeable but not ultra-strong at DAC ppm.
Very porous MOF favors high-capacity storage, yet weak low-pressure binding and uncertain humid-air stability limit DAC value.
Cation-exchanged CHA zeolite can enhance CO2 adsorption/selectivity, but water competition requires careful process design.
Low-cost zeolite is easy to shape and regenerable, yet strong water uptake in air can suppress CO2 capacity without pretreatment.
MIL-96 variant retains Al-MOF water stability with slightly improved CO2 performance; still moderate under ultra-dilute conditions.

Fiber form is easy to handle and regenerates well, yet CO2 capacity depends on ultramicropores that may be insufficient.
Scalable carbon with good cycling stability; capture at 400 ppm remains moderate without strong polar functionality.

Triamine-grafted mesoporous silica has strong chemisorption at ultra-dilute CO2, tolerates humidity, and is readily shaped/regenerated.

High-porosity MOF platform may store gases well, but humid-air stability and low-ppm CO2 working capacity are uncertain.

Mesoporous carbon is robust and easy to shape, but ultra-dilute CO2 capture depends on ultramicropores that may be limited.
Polyamine-impregnated MIL-101 combines high low-ppm uptake with workable regeneration; humidity can help but amine stability is critical.

Likely carbon-based sorbent; robust and regenerable but typically moderate at ambient CO2 without tailored ultramicropores.
Material identity is unspecified; without binding-site and stability data, DAC potential is uncertain and scored conservatively.

Zr-based framework class is comparatively water-stable; narrow pores can enhance CO2 affinity at low pressure; regeneration is typically manageable and shaping feasible.
Bio-derived/biocompatible MOF concept suggests potential for scalable synthesis; DAC performance depends on moisture stability and amine-free low-ppm affinity.
Rare-earth framework may be robust, but very high Tb content hurts cost and scalability; low-ppm CO2 performance and humidity response uncertain.
Water-stable Zr-MOF family with pore-confinement effects that can boost CO2 affinity; practical pelletization plausible; needs validation under humid low-ppm cycling.
Hydrogen-bonded/supramolecular organic frameworks can be moisture durable, but typically show modest low-pressure CO2 working capacity; mechanical shaping can be limiting.
Carbon nanofiber-based sorbent should tolerate humidity and be easy to shape; low-ppm capacity depends on microporosity and surface chemistry; regeneration is straightforward.
Open-metal-site MOF strongly co-adsorbs water, which blocks CO2 sites and degrades cyclic performance; regeneration energy rises sharply in humid operation.
Porous carbon-like material with moderate physisorption; humidity tolerance likely better than hydrophilic zeolites, but low-ppm CO2 capacity may be limited.
Fluorinated Cu-based framework shows measurable CO2 uptake and can be tuned by ligand fluorination; humidity stability and long-cycle DAC testing remain unclear.
ZIF-8 backbone is moisture resistant; functionalization can raise CO2 affinity at low pressure, but may slow kinetics and complicate regeneration if amines are present.
Fluorinated Cu-MOF reported for CO2 adsorption/separation; hydrophobic character can help in humidity, but DAC viability depends on low-ppm isotherm slope and stability.
Mg–O and amine/phosphonate functionalities could interact with CO2, but hydrate content signals strong water interactions; practical cycling and shaping data are lacking.
Polymer composite improves handling and shaping; Mg2(dobdc) provides strong CO2 sites but is moisture sensitive, so humid-air capacity and cycling remain a concern.
Zn-carboxylate framework with coordinated water suggests some hydration tolerance, but CO2 capture at low ppm and regenerability under humidity are not established.
Porous MOF candidate with unknown chemistry; likely moderate physisorption/chemisorption balance; needs proof of humidity tolerance and scalable shaping.
Mg-based frameworks can offer high CO2 affinity, but open sites often attract water; DAC suitability hinges on hydrothermal stability and regeneration energy.
3Å molecular sieve materials prioritize dehydration; CO2 access/uptake is limited compared with larger-pore adsorbents, making low-ppm capture inefficient.
Pore-expanded silica is easy to shape but weakly binds CO2 without amine functionality; humid air further reduces effective capacity via water adsorption.
DAY-type zeolite shows measurable CO2 adsorption and is mechanically robust; water competition remains the main drawback for humid DAC operation.
Raw coal can sorb CO2 but offers low selectivity and slow/variable kinetics; moisture and impurities complicate regeneration and stable DAC performance.
FAU-type zeolites are scalable and strong CO2 adsorbents, but water competes for sites and can cut working capacity in humid air; regeneration is feasible.
LTA zeolites are robust and cheap but typically more hydrophilic, so humidity suppresses CO2 capacity; still practical for engineered cycles with drying.
Oxide/graphene composites can be robust and shapeable, but CO2 affinity at low ppm is usually modest without strong basic sites; humidity effects vary with surface chemistry.
Zn-based porous coordination material may provide moderate CO2 adsorption; phosphate groups can increase polarity but also attract water; scale and cycling unknown.
MIL-family frameworks are often more robust than ultraporous Zn-MOFs; potential for reasonable low-pressure CO2 affinity, but needs humid-air cycling validation.
Zeolite framework expected to be mechanically and chemically robust; CO2 uptake can be strong but humidity competition is a key limitation for DAC.
Graphene oxide composite may aid shaping and heat transfer, but IRMOF-1 chemistry is moisture sensitive; DAC performance likely limited under humid cycling.
Mesoporous organosilica offers good shaping and stability; without strong amines/alkalinity the low-ppm CO2 capacity is limited and water can dominate adsorption.
DUT-series MOFs can be designed for improved hydrothermal stability; DAC suitability depends on low-pressure CO2 affinity and scalable pelletization.
Fluorinated MIL-140 materials show enhanced CO2 affinity/selectivity and strong framework stability; promising for humid low-ppm capture if cycling and shaping are confirmed.
Polymer-bound ZIF-8 composite improves processability and shaping; ZIF-8 is moisture resistant but low-ppm CO2 capacity remains moderate without additional functionality.
Silver-rich coordination polymer is unlikely to be cost-competitive at scale; humidity tolerance and regenerability are uncertain and may be hindered by framework fragility.
Copper coordination framework may adsorb CO2 but typically lacks proven humid-air DAC cycling; shaping and long-term stability need demonstration.
Surfactant-laden/modified pore-expanded silica is not optimized for CO2 and can strongly interact with moisture; low-ppm working capacity is expected to be low.
Bimetallic coordination material may show CO2 adsorption, but costly metals and uncertain water stability reduce scalability and practical regenerability.
Ionic/coordination polymer may have CO2 affinity, but counterions and framework stability under humidity are uncertain; scale and shaping may be difficult.
Silver-based framework is cost-limited for bulk DAC; performance under humid cycling and mechanical shaping are uncertain.
Flexible Al-MOF can show decent CO2 affinity and is more moisture tolerant than many Zn-MOFs; still needs low-ppm humid-air cycling data and scalable shaping.
Ionic-liquid incorporation can enhance CO2 interaction (especially with SCN−), but the underlying Zn-MOF water sensitivity can still limit long-term humid cycling.
Heavier water loading further blocks open metal sites and suppresses CO2 uptake; regeneration becomes water-dominated and energetically costly.
Graphene-oxide functionalization may improve handling and possibly moisture resistance, but Zn-carboxylate stability and low-ppm capture remain key risks.
Classic Zn-carboxylate framework with high surface area but poor hydrothermal robustness; humidity can degrade capacity and structure, limiting practical DAC cycling.
MOF–carbon hybrid can improve thermal conductivity and shaping; MIL-53 provides CO2 affinity while carbon improves humidity tolerance, supporting faster cycling.
Lanthanide MOFs can be relatively robust, but coordinated water indicates hydrophilicity; DAC potential depends on maintaining porosity and kinetics in humid air.
Montmorillonite-type clay is low-cost and scalable, but water strongly competes with CO2 in interlayers; useful mainly in engineered composites or dry operation.
Coal sorption is variable and moisture-sensitive; low selectivity and slow kinetics reduce practical low-ppm capture despite abundant feedstock.
Dry coal can adsorb CO2 but lacks selectivity and consistent cycling behavior; moisture swings in real air complicate regeneration and performance.
Polymer composite aids shaping and heat management; Mg2(dobdc) offers strong CO2 sites but water competition remains a major constraint in humid DAC.
Unspecified porous material; likely moderate CO2 uptake with uncertain humidity tolerance; practicality depends on whether it can be produced as durable pellets/fibers.
Non-porous polymer; without embedded sorbent chemistry it provides negligible CO2 capacity and cannot function as a standalone DAC adsorbent.
Unspecified porous material; potential depends on presence of basic sites and resistance to humidity; scale-up and regeneration characteristics are unknown.
MIL-101 family is relatively robust and high-capacity; carbon nanotubes improve shaping/transport and can mitigate humidity impacts, supporting scalable cycling.
Heteroatom-doped porous carbon can improve CO2 affinity while tolerating humidity and offering low-cost shaping; low-ppm performance depends on ultramicroporosity.
Poly(ethylene oxide) network is not a high-surface-area sorbent on its own; CO2 capture requires functional fillers or grafted amines to be competitive.
Unspecified porous material; score assumes moderate physical adsorption and unknown humidity response; practical value depends on scalable shaping and stable cycling.
Carbon-nanofiber/MOF hybrid improves processability and heat transfer; MIL-53 contributes CO2 affinity while CNF aids humidity tolerance and cycling robustness.
Contains expensive metals and likely limited scalability; coordinated water suggests hydrophilicity and uncertain cycling stability for humid DAC.
High water loading strongly competes with CO2 and can accelerate hydrolysis in Cu-BTC-type frameworks; regeneration becomes water-dominated and capacity unstable.
Flexible MOF with reasonable CO2 affinity and moderate stability; humid-air working capacity may drop but regeneration is feasible with controlled cycles.
Microporous carbon derived from nitrogen-containing precursor likely offers decent CO2 physisorption and good humidity tolerance; low-ppm performance depends on pore size distribution.
Water-stable bio-MOF variant with reported CO2/N2 molecular sieving; promising for low-ppm separations if scalable synthesis and pelletization are demonstrated.
Iron coordination compound may show some CO2 affinity, but perchlorate salt chemistry and uncertain porosity/humidity stability limit practical large-scale DAC use.
